\chapter{Resource intensity of the economy}
\label{chap:resource_intensity}
%#############################################################
%\epigraph{The conservation of natural resources is the fundamental problem.
% Unless we solve that problem it will avail us little to solve all the others.}
%{Theodore Roosevelt}
\epigraph{Without natural resources, life itself is impossible. From birth to 
death, natural resources, transformed for human use, feed, clothe, shelter, and
transport us. \ldots
% Upon them we depend for every material necessity, comfort, convenience, and protection in our lives.
Without abundant resources, prosperity is out of reach.}
{Gifford Pinchot}



Whether we are aware of it or not, 
all plant, animal, and human life on Earth depends on natural resources for survival.
Where would you be without air and water to breathe and drink?
Without minerals to make cars?
Without timber to build homes?
Without healthy soil to grow food?
Without oceans and atmosphere to accept wastes?
Without coal, oil, and methane to make electricity, gasoline, and natural gas?


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Strong sustainability}
\label{sec:resources_strong_sustainability}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

A significant sustainability challenge 
is extracting and consuming natural resources 
at a sustainable rate.
A criterion for ``strong sustainability'' is 
extracting and consuming resources 
at a rate less than their natural regeneration rates.

Resources can be classified as ``renewable'' or ``non-renewable,''
based on their regeneration rates.
Resources, such as the Sun,
that are expected to exist for millennia 
are classified as renewable.
Other resources, such as forests and other biomass,
that regenerate quickly (on the order of decades)
are also classified as renewable.
Resources, such as fossil fuels,
that regenerate slowly or not at all (such as fossil fuels)
are classified as non-renewable.

The economy, being society's metabolism,
is one aspect of life that also depends on natural resources
for its survival.
Indeed, we can say that the economy \emph{runs} on natural resources.
All goods and the infrastructure for all services depend
on manufactured objects of all types:
cars and the roads on which they travel, 
homes and the utilities that sustain life,
food and the refrigerators that maintain freshness,
toilets and the sewer systems that remove wastes.
Furthermore, the operation of all these systems requires energy.

Although any raw material can be essential for a given product,
the European Commission maintains a list Critical Raw Materials (CRMs)
with special importance across a wide range of industries.
See Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} for critical materials and industries.

