According to Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC}, 
as the energy intensity of the economy falls, 
CO$_2$ emissions will fall.
Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph} shows that
the primary energy intensity of the world economy has varied 
between 4 and 8 MJ/2017 international dollar across the last two centuries. 
Since 1970, energy intensity has been falling 
as the world economy modernizes, 
meaning that the world economy's GDP (Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph}) 
has been growing faster than primary energy consumption 
(Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}).


